{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15135"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:07:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15135"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15135"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0.13,0,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69345"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7823"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5402"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23205"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69345"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract infections (UTIs) are common infections that can affect any part of the urinary system. Various factors can increase susceptibility to these infections. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements correctly describes a risk factor for urinary tract infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Catheters increase infection risk by 3-4% per day","Schistosome eggs in bladder tissue increase infection risk","Pregnancy decreases infection risk","Urinary pH above 7 prevents infection","Frequent voiding increases infection risk"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eschistosome eggs\u003C/strong\u003E in bladder tissue causes chronic inflammation and fibrosis, creating an environment that increases susceptibility to bacterial urinary tract infections. The eggs can become calcified and create areas of damaged tissue that harbour bacteria. Schistosomiasis is an infection (bilharzia) caused by the parasitic trematode Schistosoma haematobium. Man becomes infected when coming into contact with water in which the larvae (cercariae) are swimming. The larvae enter the circulation, travel to the vesical vasculature where they reside and mature. The eggs shedded by the adult flukes penetrate the bladder mucosa and leave the host in the urine, continuing the parasite\u0027s life cycle. Problems for the host can arise when the eggs fail to penetrate the mucosa and stay trapped in the bladder wall. This can lead to an immunogenic reaction and granuloma formation, which in turn could be complicated by the development of tumours. Squamous cell carcinoma of the bladder is a recognised complication of chronic schistosomal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst schistosomiasis is not endemic in Australia, tourists travelling to parts of the world where the disease is endemic, are at risk. It is estimated that 100 million people around the world are infected with the parasite, mostly in Africa and southern Asia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheters\u003C/strong\u003E actually increase UTI risk by 5-7% per catheter-day, not 3-4%. \u003Cstrong\u003EPregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E increases UTI risk due to hormonal changes and pressure on the bladder. An alkaline \u003Cstrong\u003Eurinary pH\u003C/strong\u003E (above 7) actually promotes bacterial growth. \u003Cstrong\u003EFrequent voiding\u003C/strong\u003E helps prevent UTIs by flushing out bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors for UTIs include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFemale anatomy (shorter urethra)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary tract obstruction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmunosuppression\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESexual activity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urinary schistosomiasis causes chronic inflammation and fibrosis, increasing risk of urinary tract infections","Urinary catheters increase UTI risk by 5-7% per catheter-day","Risk factors for UTIs include anatomical abnormalities, immunosuppression, and urinary obstruction"],"references":["Sabih A, Leslie SW. Complicated Urinary Tract Infections. 2023 Nov 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613784","Bilsen MP, Jongeneel RMH, Schneeberger C, Platteel TN, van Nieuwkoop C, Mody L, Caterino JM, Geerlings SE, K\u00f6ves B, Wagenlehner F, Conroy SP, Visser LG, Lambregts MMC. Definitions of Urinary Tract Infection in Current Research: A Systematic Review. Open Forum Infect Dis. 2023 Jun 27;10(7):ofad332. doi: 10.1093/ofid/ofad332. PMID: 37426954; PMCID: PMC10323732","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Flores-Mireles AL, Walker JN, Caparon M, Hultgren SJ. Urinary tract infections: epidemiology, mechanisms of infection and treatment options. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2015 May;13(5):269-84. doi: 10.1038/nrmicro3432. Epub 2015 Apr 8. PMID: 25853778; PMCID: PMC4457377."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15135"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T20:00:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T20:00:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7823"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69345"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"